Air Quality analysis

First Data Set

PM2.5 Emissions Data . This file contains a data frame with all of the PM2.5 emissions data for 1999, 2002, 2005, and 2008. For each year, the table contains number of tons of PM2.5 emitted from a specific type of source for the entire year.Here are the first five rows.

#Reading the dataset
nei <- readRDS("./R_course/summarySCC_PM25.rds")
head(nei)
      fips      SCC Pollutant Emissions  type year
  4  09001 10100401  PM25-PRI    15.714 POINT 1999
  8  09001 10100404  PM25-PRI   234.178 POINT 1999
  12 09001 10100501  PM25-PRI     0.128 POINT 1999
  16 09001 10200401  PM25-PRI     2.036 POINT 1999
  20 09001 10200504  PM25-PRI     0.388 POINT 1999
  24 09001 10200602  PM25-PRI     1.490 POINT 1999

  • fips: A five-digit number (represented as a string) indicating the U.S. county

  • SCC: The name of the source as indicated by a digit string (see source code classification table)

  • Pollutant: A string indicating the pollutant

  • Emissions: Amount of PM2.5 emitted, in tons

  • type: The type of source (point, non-point, on-road, or non-road)

  • year: The year of emissions recorded

Which type of emission has emitted the most pollutant in years 1999?

Year 1999

if(!exists("NEI")){
    NEI <- readRDS("./R_course/summarySCC_PM25.rds")
}
if(!exists("SCC")){
    SCC <- readRDS("./R_course/Source_Classification_Code.rds")
}
# merge the two data sets
if(!exists("NEISCC")){
    NEISCC <- merge(NEI, SCC, by="SCC")
}

library(ggplot2)
#Subsetting only the data of year 1999
subsetNEI <- NEI[NEI$year==1999, ]
aggregatedTotalByYear <- aggregate(Emissions ~ type+fips, subsetNEI, sum)
g <- ggplot(aggregatedTotalByYear, aes(factor(type), Emissions))
g <- g + geom_bar(stat="identity") +
    xlab("Types") +
    ylab(expression('Total PM'[2.5]*" Emissions")) +
    ggtitle('Emissions by the respective types in the year 1999')
print(g)

Among Industrial Processes and Waste Disposal sources which source has emitted the most pollution?

if(!exists("NEI")){
    NEI <- readRDS("./R_Course/summarySCC_PM25.rds")
}
if(!exists("SCC")){
    SCC <- readRDS("./R_course/Source_Classification_Code.rds")
}
# merge the two data sets
if(!exists("NEISCC")){
    NEISCC <- merge(NEI, SCC, by="SCC")
}

library(ggplot2)
library(ggplot2)

# 24510 is Baltimore, see plot2.R, 06037 is LA CA
# Searching for ON-ROAD type in NEI
# Don't actually know it this is the intention, but searching for 'motor' in SCC only gave a subset (non-cars)
sub <- NEISCC[(NEISCC$SCC.Level.One=="Industrial Processes"|NEISCC$SCC.Level.One=="Waste Disposal, Treatment, and Recovery"),]
aggregatedTotalByYearAndType <- aggregate(Emissions ~ year + SCC.Level.One, sub, sum)
aggregatedTotalByYearAndType$SCC.Level.One[aggregatedTotalByYearAndType$SCC.Level.One=="Waste Disposal, Treatment, and Recovery"] <- "Waste Disposal"

g <- ggplot(aggregatedTotalByYearAndType, aes(factor(year), Emissions))
 g <- g + facet_grid(. ~ SCC.Level.One)
g <- g + geom_bar(stat="identity") +
    xlab("Year") +
    ylab(expression('Total PM'[2.5]*" Emissions")) +
    ggtitle('Amount of pollutant emitted by each type of emission')
plot(g)

Across the United States, how have emissions from coal combustion-related sources changed from 19992008?

NEI <- readRDS("./R_course/summarySCC_PM25.rds")
SCC <- readRDS("./R_course/Source_Classification_Code.rds")

# merge the two data sets
 NEISCC <- merge(NEI, SCC, by="SCC")


library(ggplot2)
library(ggplot2)

# fetch all NEIxSCC records with Short.Name (SCC) Coal
coalMatches <- grepl("coal", NEISCC$Short.Name, ignore.case=TRUE)
subsetNEISCC <- NEISCC[coalMatches, ]

aggregatedTotalByYear <- aggregate(Emissions ~ year, subsetNEISCC, sum)
g <- ggplot(aggregatedTotalByYear, aes(factor(year), Emissions))
g <- g + geom_bar(stat="identity") +
  xlab("Year") +
  ylab(expression('Total PM'[2.5]*" Emissions")) +
  ggtitle('Total Emissions from coal sources from 1999 to 2008')
print(g)

Of the four types of sources indicated by the type (point, nonpoint, onroad, nonroad) variable, which of these four sources have seen decreases in emissions from 19992008 for Baltimore City? Which have seen increases in emissions from 19992008?

SCC <- readRDS("./R_course/Source_Classification_Code.rds")
library(ggplot2)
library(ggplot2)
# 24510 is Baltimore.
#Combing three columns now (Emission,Year and type)
subsetNEI <- NEI[NEI$fips=="24510", ]
aggregatedTotalByYearAndType <- aggregate(Emissions ~ year + type, subsetNEI, sum)
# Use the ggplot2 plotting system to make a plot.

print(g)

Compare the emissions of four type of source between Baltimore City and Los Angeles county.Which type has made a greater impact on them?

NEI <- readRDS("./R_course/summarySCC_PM25.rds")
SCC <- readRDS("./R_course/Source_Classification_Code.rds")
library(ggplot2)
library(ggplot2)
# 24510 is Baltimore.
#Combing three columns now (Emission,Year and type)
subsetNEI <- NEI[(NEI$fips=="24510"|NEI$fips=="06037"), ]
aggregatedTotalByYearAndType <- aggregate(Emissions ~ year + type+fips, subsetNEI, sum)
aggregatedTotalByYearAndType$fips[aggregatedTotalByYearAndType$fips=="24510"] <- "Baltimore, MD"
aggregatedTotalByYearAndType$fips[aggregatedTotalByYearAndType$fips=="06037"] <- "Los Angeles, CA"
# Use the ggplot2 plotting system to make a plot.
g <- ggplot(aggregatedTotalByYearAndType, aes(year, Emissions, color = type))
g <- g + geom_line() +facet_grid(.~fips)+
    xlab("Year") +
    ylab(expression('Total PM'[2.5]*" Emissions")) +
    ggtitle('Total Emissions in Baltimore City,Maryland and Los Angeles County from 1999 to 2008')
print(g)

Which county had the highest and lowest emission of PM2.5?

#Combining the emission and fips column of the dataset using aggregrate function
nei <- readRDS("./R_course/summarySCC_PM25.rds")
aggregateTotalFips <- aggregate(Emissions~year+fips,nei,sum)
#Plotting it using barplot
barplot(height = aggregateTotalFips$Emissions,names.arg = aggregateTotalFips$fips,xlab="Fips", ylab=expression('Total PM'[2.5]*' emission'),main=expression('Total PM'[2.5]*' emissions of various Counties'))

max(aggregateTotalFips$Emissions)

min(aggregateTotalFips$Emissions)

# 24510 is Baltimore, see plot2.R, 06037 is LA CA
# Searching for ON-ROAD type in NEI
# Don't actually know it this is the intention, but searching for 'motor' in SCC only gave a subset (non-cars)

Have total emissions for PM2.5 decreased in the United States from 1999 to 2008?

#Combining the emission and year column of the dataset using aggregrate function
nei <- readRDS("./R_course/summarySCC_PM25.rds")
aggregateTotalYear <- aggregate(Emissions~year,nei,sum)
#Plotting it using barplot
barplot(height = aggregateTotalYear$Emissions,names.arg = aggregateTotalYear$year,xlab="Years", ylab=expression('Total PM'[2.5]*' emission'),main=expression('Total PM'[2.5]*' emissions at various years'))

Conclusion:

  • It is clearly observed that from the year 1999-2008 non-point type of emission has emitted the most PM2.5 pollutant where as on-road type emission has emitted the least pollutant .This analysis is applicable to all the counties in the USA.

  • Among the pollutant emission sources the Industries have caused the major damage as compared to waste disposal , and waste treatment.

  • From the on-road type of emission , the pollutant emitted by the bikes and heavy duty vehicles (Trucks) are nearly equal.

  • To compare between Baltimore City and Los Angeles County , Baltimore have emitted less pollutant and that to also at a gradually decreasing rate, where as in Los Angeles pollutant were emitted more as compared to Baltimore and that to at very high rate which increased each year.

  • County named Yukon-Koyukuk Census Area located in Alaska was the county that emitted the highest emission with 647413.3 tons of PM2.5 pollutant.

  • There were Six counties which emitted 0 tons of pollutant.

  • It was observed that even in Yukon-Koyukuk Census Area emission was at height in the year 2002 and then it fell down in 2005 and 2008.

  • Lastly we conclude that emission of PM2.5 pollutant has decreased over the time period from 1999-2008 ,with 2008 having the least amount of emission.
